      .preparation_col.head_aftr_none
        %h2
          How do GAMSAT
          %sup ®
          Essay Quotes work?
        %p
          In each of the two tasks in GAMSAT
          %sup ®
          Section 2, you will be presented with five quotes that relate to one or more themes. Your task is to identify one of these themes and write a piece in response. Thus, it is important to remember that the quotes are there as a prompt or a guide, rather than a traditional essay question. It is not necessary to respond directly to any or all of the quotes, but rather to respond to the themes and ideas contained in the quotes.
      .preparation_col.head_aftr_none
        %h2#whatIsSection2
          Understanding the Theme
        %p.mtop_zero
          The first step to writing your GAMSAT
          %sup ®
          essay is to dissect and understand the themes presented to you. This is not always as straightforward as it seems - There are often multiple themes included within a set of quotes. Nevertheless, the process can be summarised as below:
          %ol
            %li
              Read the first two quotes
            %li
              Compare both quotes - Are there any related words or ideas?
            %li
              Note down any common words/themes
            %li
              Read the third quote - Are there any common ideas you can add to your list?
            %li
              Repeat with the rest of the quotes
        %p.mtop_zero
          After this process you should have a “word cloud” that points to the key overarching theme - However, it’s important to note that the stimuli are often designed such that there are a number of sub-themes that may be relevant. The point here is not to limit the scope of your writing but to expand it and bring in other relevant ideas - In fact it’s fine to draw on either the overarching theme or a sub-theme, so long as you demonstrate that you have actively engaged with the stimuli.
        %p.mtop_zero
          Let’s look at a worked example below:
        .highlight_box.gamsat-prep.mbot20
          %ol
            %li
              I don’t know half of you half as well as I shouldn’t like; and I like less than half of you half as well as you deserve.
              %i (J.R.R. Tolkien)
            %li
              After a good dinner one can forgive anybody, even one’s own relations.
              %i (Oscar Wilde)
            %li
              Water cannot be cut and blood is thicker than water.
              %i (Malaysian Proverb)
            %li
              It is an absolute human certainty that no one can know his own beauty or perceive a sense of his own worth until it has been reflected back to him in the mirror of another loving, caring human being.
              %i (John Joseph Powell)
            %li
              Isn’t everyone a part of everyone else?
              %i (Budd Schulberg)
        %p.mtop_zero
          What are some themes you can identify? Let’s break it down quote by quote:
        .tbl_responsive.fl_none
          %table.table.cstm_tbl.table-bordered.table-condensed.custom_table_data
            %thead
              %th.text-center.width75 Quote
              %th.text-center Themes
            %tbody
              %tr
                %td
                  %i
                    I don’t know half of you half as well as I shouldn’t like; and I like less than half of you half as well as you deserve.
                %td
                  Relationship & Friendships
                  %br
                  Community & Social Norms
                  %br
                  Commentary on modern relationships
              %tr
                %td
                  %i
                    After a good dinner one can forgive anybody, even one’s own relations.
                %td
                  Family
                  %br
                  Forgiveness & Reconciliation
                  %br
                  Conflict
              %tr
                %td
                  %i
                    Water cannot be cut and blood is thicker than water.
                %td
                  Family
                  %br
                  Loyalty
              %tr
                %td
                  %i
                    It is an absolute human certainty that no one can know his own beauty or perceive a sense of his own worth until it has been reflected back to him in the mirror of another loving, caring human being.
                %td
                  Relationships
                  %br
                  Self-worth
                  %br
                  Commentary of social interaction
              %tr
                %td
                  %i
                    Isn’t everyone a part of everyone else?
                %td
                  Community & Society
                  %br
                  Individualism vs Collectivism
        %p
          As you can see there are multiple themes that you could draw from the above stimuli - It’s important to note that you don’t need to write about a theme that is presented in all of the quotes provided, you can choose a theme that may only appear once or twice in the stimuli.

