          and something you should aim to start from early on. Indeed, a lot of the preparation for Section 2 of the GAMSAT
          %sup ®
          Exam should revolve around simply writing a lot of essays, at least one a week. However, this advice comes with several caveats:
          %ol
            %li
              %p.mtop_zero
                You need to get feedback on your essays. It is vital that you get your friends, family, tutors and anyone else to read these essays, and be modest and inviting of critique. It is of utmost importance to be criticised and then learn from your mistakes. GradReady has an essay marking service where you can get 10 essays marked by our expert tutors with personal feedback within 72 hours.
                %a{href: "/gamsat-preparation-courses/custom", target: "_blank"}
                  %strong Learn more here.
            %li
              %p.mtop_zero
                You need to possess a great deal of self-critique. After every essay you write, you must read it out loud to yourself, and listen if it makes sense. You can find some free
                %a{href: "/gamsat-example-essay",target: "_blank"}
                  %strong
                    example Marked GAMSAT
                    %sup ®
                    Essays here.
            %li
              %p.mtop_zero
                Don’t feel the need to write under time pressure from the word go. It’s more important that you develop and improve your essay writing skills before gradually applying realistic time pressure.
            %li
              %p.mtop_zero
                You need to vary the type of essays that you write! You should make sure you try argumentative, personal reflective essays,
                %a{href: "/posts/gamsat-preparation-courses/writing-the-creative-gamsat-essay",target: "_blank"}
                  %strong fictional creative essays,
                poetry, and any other medium that can work in the GAMSAT
                %sup ®
                exam. Even though it’s recommended you write an argumentative essay, you are able to write in almost any style in the ‘reflective’ essay segment – this is meant to be a creative endeavour and demonstrate that you can identify, and express emotions of the characters involved.
